<TITLE> Ecuador bans state workers from Halloween fun </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 QUITO, Oct 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Ecuador's leftist president, Rafael Correa, has prohibited state workers from asking for their Halloween treats on Wednesday, saying Ecuadoreans should celebrate their own holidays instead of foreign festivities. "Public institutions are banned from celebrating Halloween," a government release quoted Correa as saying on a radio broadcast. "We have our own beautiful celebrations ... We are a nationalist government." Correa urged Ecuadoreans to celebrate the national day for the flag's coat of arms instead, while the education ministry on Tuesday told school officials to avoid Halloween celebrations. Correa, a US-trained economist, has kept relations cool with Washington, calling US President George W Bush a dimwit and vowing not to renew the lease on an air base used by the US military to fight drug trafficking in the Andean region. Correa's move mirrors that of close ally and US foe Venezuelan leader Hugo Chavez, who has urged children to ignore US heroes like Superman and forget Halloween which he has says spreads terror. Chavez, a self-styled socialist revolutionary allied with Cuba, is using his hefty oil revenues to battle Washington's influence over Latin America and counter what he calls are US "imperialist" trade polici
